---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const description =
  "Engines — Plain Theory Labs";
---

<BaseLayout title="Engines — Plain Theory Labs" description={description}>
  <section class="section prose">
    <h1>Engines</h1>

    <p class="thesis">
      The PTL certification framework is built from nine analytical engines.
      PROFILE characterizes the cluster before analysis begins. Five engines grade
      specific dimensions of infrastructure operations. GRADE aggregates their
      findings into a PTL Score and certification tier. ATLAS converts the
      certification into a ranked action plan. CLAW automates continuous data
      collection from inside the cluster environment.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>ACE — Adaptive Compute Efficiency Engine</h2>

    <p>
      ACE is the foundation of the certification framework. It ingests Slurm
      scheduler exports and GPU telemetry from an HPC cluster, scores every job
      against a documented efficiency methodology, and produces graded findings
      with traceable assumptions. The question ACE answers is concrete: of the
      GPU resources your jobs requested, how much was actually used, and where
      is the gap recoverable through right-sizing or scheduler policy?
    </p>

    <p>
      Every recommendation ACE produces carries a confidence label that reflects
      the quality of the underlying data. A recommendation derived from a proxy
      estimate is labeled differently than one derived from direct DCGM telemetry.
      The engine withholds recommendations it cannot defend — the safety overlay
      is a design constraint, not a heuristic.
    </p>

    <p>
      ACE is validated on the MIT Supercloud HPCA22 dataset, a published
      peer-reviewed dataset from a production HPC system. 73,367 jobs analyzed.
      Average GPU utilization: 25.7%.
    </p>

    <div class="findings">
      <p><strong>gpu_efficiency_score</strong>primary metric — weighted utilization vs. requested allocation</p>
    </div>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>COOL — Cooling Operations Optimization Layer</h2>

    <p>
      COOL grades the thermal efficiency of the facility housing your compute.
      At Level 1, it works from self-reported power usage effectiveness (PUE)
      and facility metadata — cooling type, location, facility age. At Level 2,
      it ingests building management system timeseries data and correlates cooling
      load directly with ACE job records, enabling per-job thermal attribution.
    </p>

    <p>
      PUE is the standard metric for data center energy efficiency, but a raw PUE
      number has no policy value without a benchmark. COOL grades PUE against
      climate-adjusted benchmarks drawn from ASHRAE standards, accounting for the
      fact that a facility in Minnesota has a different achievable PUE than one
      in Texas. The grade reflects performance against what is achievable, not
      against an absolute threshold that ignores geography.
    </p>

    <div class="findings">
      <p><strong>cool_efficiency_score</strong>PUE delta vs. climate-adjusted ASHRAE benchmark</p>
    </div>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>FLUX — Facility Load and Utilization Index</h2>

    <p>
      FLUX grades the carbon accounting methodology an organization uses to report
      its energy footprint. The quality of carbon accounting varies enormously —
      from simple grid-average emission factors to location-matched hourly marginal
      emissions with verified renewable energy certificates. FLUX grades the method
      itself, not just the number it produces.
    </p>

    <p>
      FLUX also detects greenwashing: cases where an organization claims renewable
      energy coverage that is not supported by the accounting method used. An
      organization claiming significant renewable coverage while using unbundled
      RECs with grid-average accounting is flagged. The finding is included in the
      certification record with the supporting methodology disclosed.
    </p>

    <div class="findings">
      <p><strong>flux_methodology_score</strong>carbon accounting quality grade — method rigor and renewable claim validity</p>
    </div>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>PACE — Predictive Allocation and Cluster Efficiency</h2>

    <p>
      PACE grades scheduler policy — the operational decisions that determine how
      jobs are queued, prioritized, and allocated across the cluster. Backfill
      scheduling, preemption, fairshare, and priority decay all affect utilization
      in ways that ACE can measure at the job level but cannot fully explain without
      knowing the policy context. PACE provides that context.
    </p>

    <p>
      PACE cross-correlates with ACE findings to distinguish systemic inefficiency
      from workload-driven inefficiency. If a cluster's low GPU utilization is
      concentrated in specific queues with particular scheduler configurations, that
      is a different finding than utilization that is uniformly low across all
      workloads. The distinction matters for the ATLAS action plan.
    </p>

    <div class="findings">
      <p><strong>pace_composite_score</strong>scheduler efficiency — accuracy, queue incentives, fragmentation</p>
    </div>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>CORE — Capital and Operations Resource Evaluator</h2>

    <p>
      CORE grades the hardware fit of your GPU fleet against your actual workloads.
      A cluster optimized for large-batch training that is running primarily inference
      workloads is operating inefficient hardware regardless of its utilization rate.
      CORE evaluates whether the GPUs deployed are the right GPUs for the work
      being done.
    </p>

    <p>
      CORE also grades fleet age and embodied carbon. Hardware that is past its
      optimal operational window carries increasing embodied carbon per unit of
      useful work. The CORE score combines hardware-workload fit, fleet age, and
      embodied carbon into a single efficiency grade, weighted to reflect that fit
      is the dominant factor in near-term optimization decisions.
    </p>

    <div class="findings">
      <p><strong>core_efficiency_score</strong>hardware-workload fit (40%) · fleet age (35%) · embodied carbon (25%)</p>
    </div>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>GRADE — Granular Rating for AI Data center Efficiency</h2>

    <p>
      GRADE is the aggregation layer. It ingests the output of every engine that
      has run against an organization's data, weights the scores according to the
      published methodology, and computes a composite that determines the
      certification tier. Engines with no data are excluded from the composite —
      the weights of present engines are rescaled to sum to 1.0, so partial
      certification is a meaningful result rather than a penalized one.
    </p>

    <p>
      GRADE produces a JSON findings file and a zero-dependency HTML certification
      report. The report includes engine findings, the path to the next tier, an
      ATLAS recommendations section, and full methodology disclosure. The report
      is designed to travel — any stakeholder can open it on any machine without
      specialized tooling.
    </p>

    <div class="findings">
      <p><strong>certification tier</strong>PENDING · BASELINE · DEVELOPING · CAPABLE · OPTIMIZED · FRONTIER</p>
    </div>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>ATLAS — Actionable Trajectory and Longitudinal Analysis</h2>

    <p>
      ATLAS converts the certification findings into a prioritized action plan.
      For each engine gap — the distance between an organization's current score
      and the next tier threshold — ATLAS computes a priority score based on gap
      size, engine weight in GRADE, and an operational impact factor that reflects
      how tractable the improvement is. The result is a ranked list of actions
      ordered by expected certification impact.
    </p>

    <p>
      ATLAS also produces peer benchmark percentiles, placing an organization's
      scores in context against the distribution of other certified organizations.
      Where prior period data exists, ATLAS projects a linear trajectory and
      estimates how many assessment cycles the current improvement rate implies
      before reaching the next tier.
    </p>

    <div class="findings">
      <p><strong>ranked recommendations</strong>priority = gap × engine weight × operational impact factor</p>
    </div>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>PROFILE — Cluster Profile Engine</h2>

    <p>
      PROFILE runs before any other engine. It characterizes the cluster — scheduler
      type, GPU fleet composition, telemetry availability — and produces a routing
      manifest that determines which input paths the downstream engines will use.
      The result is that each engine receives data matched to how the cluster actually
      operates, not a forced fit to a single collection method.
    </p>

    <p>
      PROFILE detects the scheduler in use (Slurm, Kubernetes, Ray) and the telemetry
      sources available (sacct exports, DCGM metrics, k8s resource data, CLAW
      continuous streams). It outputs an <code>ace_input_path</code> and a
      <code>pace_input_path</code> used by every downstream engine. Organizations
      with multiple schedulers or mixed telemetry sources are handled correctly rather
      than defaulted.
    </p>

    <div class="findings">
      <p><strong>ace_input_path</strong>claw · dcgm · k8s_metrics · sacct — in priority order</p>
      <p><strong>pace_input_path</strong>kubernetes · ray · slurm</p>
    </div>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>CLAW — NemoClaw Intake Agent</h2>

    <p>
      CLAW is the automated data collection layer. It runs as an agent inside an
      organization's OpenShell environment, pulls cluster telemetry on a continuous
      schedule, and delivers structured JSON to the PTL engine stack without requiring
      manual export steps. A one-time setup replaces the recurring operational burden
      of preparing data for each assessment cycle.
    </p>

    <p>
      CLAW v0.1 supports manual JSON delivery with a documented schema. CLAW v1.0
      adds a privacy router: raw telemetry stays inside the organization's environment;
      only the computed metrics transit to PTL. Organizations that require strict data
      residency can run CLAW in local mode and deliver only aggregated findings.
    </p>

    <div class="findings">
      <p><strong>collection mode</strong>continuous automated · manual export · local-only privacy mode</p>
      <p><strong>scheduler support</strong>Slurm · Kubernetes · Ray</p>
    </div>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <p>Questions about the methodology or how the engines work in practice? Write to us at jesus@plaintheory.org.</p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
